London is an amazing city with a long and fairytale-like history that reveals itself in everyday life in its architectural masterpieces, cultural and social diversity, and unbelievable stories1. Did you know that what you think of London is actually just a small urban area part of the Greater London region? The city of London covers only 1.2 square miles and has a population of around 7,500 residents. As such, the city of London is actually the smallest city in England1.

Paris is the capital and most populous city of France1. It is known for its rich history, culture, and architecture. The city is home to many famous landmarks such as the Eiffel Tower, the Louvre Museum, and Notre-Dame Cathedral2. Paris is also famous for its food, fashion, and art. The city has a population of over 2 million people1 and is located in the north-central part of France3. Did you know that Paris plans to make the Seine the centerpiece of the 2024 Olympic Games? Long-term efforts to clean up the river will allow swimming events to take place in its waters4.

Tokyo is the capital and most populous city of Japan1. It is also one of the worlds most populous cities, with a population of over 13 million people2. Tokyo is known for its rich history, culture, and architecture. The city is home to many famous landmarks such as the Tokyo Skytree, the Imperial Palace, and the Meiji Shrine2. Tokyo is also famous for its food, fashion, and art. The city has a lot of museums, including the Tokyo National Museum and the Edo-Tokyo Museum2. Did you know that Tokyo is actually made up of 23 central city wards and multiple cities, towns and villages west of the city center? The Izu and Ogasawara Islands are also part of Tokyo2.

Melbourne is the capital and most populous city of the Australian state of Victoria1. It was founded on the Yarra River in 1835 after an abortive bid in 1803 to establish a settlement inside the Port Phillip Bay heads near Sorrento2. The Port Phillip District gained independence from New South Wales in 18502. Melbourne boomed in the 1850s as a result of the gold rush in the region to the north2 and became a town in 1842 and a city in 18473. Melbournes history is rich and diverse, with many landmarks such as the Royal Exhibition Building, Flinders Street Station, and Federation Square4. Melbourne is also known for its food, fashion, and art. The city has a population of over 5 million people1.

Egypt is a country in northeastern Africa with a long and rich history that dates back to the 6th-4th millennia BCE1. It is considered a cradle of civilization and saw some of the earliest developments of writing, agriculture, urbanization, organized religion, and central government2. Ancient Egyptian civilization coalesced around 3150 BC with the political unification of Upper and Lower Egypt under the first king of the First Dynasty, Narmer1. The Nile River has played a significant role in Egypts history, providing fertile banks and delta for agriculture and transportation1. Today, Egypt is known for its pyramids, temples, and tombs that have fascinated people for centuries3.

Dubai is a city in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and the capital of the Emirate of Dubai. It is known for its luxurious lifestyle, modern architecture, and vibrant nightlife1. Dubai is home to many famous landmarks such as the Burj Khalifa, the worlds tallest building2, and the Palm Jumeirah, an artificial island that is shaped like a palm tree2. The city is also famous for its shopping malls, including the Dubai Mall, which is one of the largest malls in the world2. Dubai has a lot of attractions and activities to offer, such as desert safaris, water parks, and indoor skiing3. The city has a population of over 3 million people1.
